  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Although \"A Constellation of Courts\" has not yet amassed citations or community discussions, its commercial presence on platforms like Amazon and Goodreads suggests a level of interest within the academic community and beyond. The book is likely to resonate with readers interested in legal studies and related fields.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Published in 2021 by Leuven University Press, \"A Constellation of Courts\" has established a commercial linkage in the academic landscape, albeit without notable citations or mentions in public discourse. Its availability on major retail platforms indicates that the work has attracted some interest, especially among practitioners and scholars in legal studies.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The absence of online mentions across platforms such as Wikipedia, Reddit, or Bluesky signifies that while the work has potential, it has not yet fostered significant community engagement or discourse. This may reflect the niche nature of its subject matter or the emerging status of its ideas in the wider academic conversation.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Despite the lack of public discussion or academic citations to date, the inferred evidence of commercial linkage emphasizes a recognized relevance for those operating within the judicial and legal realms. Moreover, the book's alignment with a single Sustainable Development Goal indicates a degree of policy relevance, contributing to broader discussions around legal frameworks.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">In conclusion, while \"A Constellation of Courts\" has not yet reached impactful milestones in terms of academic or popular discourse, its commercial presence hints at an underlying interest. Continued engagement through academic networks or social platforms may yet amplify its visibility and relevance in the discourse surrounding judicial systems.</p>",
